featured_reviews.review_id:
It was built by the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahanbetween 1650 and 1656 at a cost of 1 million rupees, and was inaugurated by Imam Syed Abdul Ghafoor Shah Bukhari from Bukhara, present-day Uzbekistan. The mosque was completed in 1656 AD with three great gates, four towers and two 40 metres high minarets constructed with strips of red sandstoneand white marble. The courtyard can accommodate more than 25,000 people. There are three domes on the terrace which are surrounded by the two minarets. On the floor, a total of 899 black borders are marked for worshippers. The architectural plan of Badshahi Masjid, built by Shah Jahan's son Aurangzeb at Lahore, Pakistan, is similar to the Jama Masjid.

featured_reviews.review_id:
It was built by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahanbetween 1644 and 1656 at a cost of 1 million rupees, and was inaugurated by an Imam from Bukhara, present-day Uzbekistan. The mosque was completed in 1656 AD with three great gates, four towers and two 40 metres high minaretsconstructed with strips of red sandstone and white marble. The courtyard can accommodate more than 25,000 people. There are three domes on the terrace which are surrounded by the two minarets. On the floor, a total of 899 black borders are marked for worshippers. The architectural plan of Badshahi Masjid, built by Shah Jahan's son Aurangzeb at Lahore, Pakistan, is similar to the Jama Masjid.

HistoryEdit

Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan built the Jama Masjid between 1644 and 1656. It was constructed by more than 5000 workers. It was originally called Masjid-i-Jahan Numa, meaning 'mosque commanding view of the world'. The construction was done under the supervision of Saadullah Khan, wazir (or prime minister) during Shah Jahan's reign. The cost of the construction at the time was one million Rupees.[1] Shah Jahan also built the Taj Mahal, at Agra and the Red Fortin New Delhi, which stands opposite the Jama Masjid.

The Jama Masjid was completed in 1656 AD (1066 AH).[1] The mosque was inaugurated by an Imam Bukhari, a mullah from Bukhara, Uzbekistan, on 23 July 1656, on the invitation from Shah Jahan.[2]About 25,000 people can pray in the courtyard at a time .[3][4] The mosque is commonly called "Jama" which means Friday.[1]

After the British victory in the Revolt of 1857, they confiscated the mosque and stationed their soldiers there. They also wanted to destroy the mosque as an act of punishment to the city. But due to opposition faced, the demolition was not done.[5]

The iconic mosque is one of the last monuments built under Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan. After the construction of the monument in 1656, it remained the royal mosque of the emperors until the end of the Mughal period.

During 1948, the last Nizam of Hyderabad, Asaf Jah VII was asked for a donation of Rs75,000 to repair one-fourth of the mosque floor. The Nizam instead sanctioned Rs3 lakh, stating that the remaining three-fourths of the mosque should not look old.

Now masjid is rejuvenating the outermost and middle structure of the masjid is in the process of rejuvenation.
Children came here to see eye-catching colorful fishes inside the pond.

Huge mosque with large pond with colorful fishes huge structure all its have.

If you want to visit Meerut, don't forget to visit this holy place once and pray there for me also.

Hope you like this review.

Zadeed Masjid is a prominent mosque located in the village of Khandrawali, in the District of Shamli, Uttar Pradesh, India. The mosque holds great historical and religious significance for the local community. With its grand structure and beautiful architecture, Zadeed Masjid stands as a testament to the rich cultural heritage of the region. It serves as a place of worship for the Muslim community, bringing people together in prayer and reflection.

The origins of Zadeed Masjid can be traced back several centuries, with some claiming it to be more than 300 years old. The mosque has undergone several renovations and expansions over the years to accommodate the growing number of worshippers. The design of the mosque reflects a blend of traditional Mughal and Indo-Islamic architectural styles, with intricate carvings and elaborate gardens surrounding the premises. Its towering minarets and dome are a testament to the craftsmanship and dedication put into its construction.

Apart from its religious significance, Zadeed Masjid also plays a pivotal role in fostering community spirit and social cohesion. The mosque serves as a platform for various educational and charitable activities, promoting literacy and providing assistance to the underprivileged. It serves as a gathering place for festivals and events that celebrate the Islamic calendar, bringing the community together in joyous occasions. The mosque also serves as a hub for interfaith dialogue, promoting understanding and tolerance among different religious communities in the area.

In conclusion, Zadeed Masjid in the village of Khandrawali, District Shamli, stands as a symbol of rich cultural heritage and religious devotion. Its historical significance, architectural splendor, and community involvement make it a vital part of the local community. The mosque continues to be a place of worship, education, and social cohesion, bringing people of all backgrounds together in unity.

featured_reviews.review_id:
My recent visit to the Nizamuddin Tabligh Markaz in Delhi was an extraordinary experience that left a deep impression on me. This spiritual center is not only of great significance to the local community but also serves as the hub for the global Tabligh Jamaat movement. I had the privilege of being there to offer Maghrib and Isha prayers, and the entire experience was awe-inspiring.

The sheer scale of the gathering was astounding, with nearly 2,000 people congregating within the seven-story building. What struck me immediately was the diversity of the attendees, including a substantial number of international Tabligh workers. This truly reflected the global reach and influence of the Tabligh Jamaat movement.

One aspect that deserves special mention is the remarkable organization and management of the event. The volunteers working diligently inside the Markaz demonstrated incredible skill in maintaining order, ensuring proper space management, and guiding visitors. Given the sheer number of people present, their efforts were nothing short of commendable. The volunteers' dedication and commitment to their roles were evident, and their polite and well-trained demeanor made the experience even more pleasant.

Cleanliness, despite the large gathering, was well-maintained, which is a testament to the meticulous planning and execution by the organizers. This added to the overall positive atmosphere and enhanced the spiritual experience for everyone present.

One of the highlights of my visit was attending a speech by a notable Islamic scholar after the Maghrib prayer. The scholar's eloquent and enlightening speech left a lasting impact on me. I later learned that such speeches are a regular feature, occurring after each of the obligatory prayers, and feature senior Islamic scholars from various parts of the world. This commitment to spiritual education and discourse was truly impressive and provided a unique opportunity for attendees to gain insights and knowledge.

Beyond the spiritual experience inside the Markaz, the area surrounding it was vibrant and full of life. Nizamuddin is renowned for its quality street food and restaurants. Karim's, a famous Delhi institution known for its delectable Mughlai cuisine, is just a stone's throw away. Exploring the culinary delights of the area added another layer of richness to my visit.

In conclusion, my visit to the Nizamuddin Tabligh Markaz in Delhi was an enriching and spiritually fulfilling experience. It showcased the unity and diversity of the Tabligh Jamaat movement on a global scale. The dedication of the volunteers, the educational opportunities, the spiritual environment, and the vibrant surroundings made it a memorable visit. I left with a sense of peace, enlightenment, and a deep appreciation for the remarkable work being done by the Tabligh Jamaat community. It's an experience I will cherish and hope to revisit in the future.

NB: Isha jamat pryer is at 10 pm.

featured_reviews.review_id:
ALLAHUAKBAR...
What to describe about this place.
Alhamdulillah visited this place yesterday. That was my life time dzire to visit markaz nizamuddin. Actually i was supposed to be there years ago along with jamat. But unfortunately i couldn't. Somehow i went there yesterday at Evening and Offered Namaz e Asar in the Banglewali Masjid Alhamdulillah.
Wherever i see in the masjid i only find members of jamath from all over the world. Allapak un sab ko aur unke tufel sari ummat ko hidayat ata farmay..
And Ladies those who are with jamath can only stay there otherwise there is no any facility for other women to stay or offer namaz neither in masjid nor in Hazraths Premises.

featured_reviews.review_id: Nizamuddin Markaz, also called Banglewali Masjid, is a mosque located in Nizamuddin West in South Delhi, India. It is the birthplace and global centre of the Tablighi Jamaat, the missionary and reformist movement started by Muhammad Ilyas Kandhlawi in 1926.
